Definition

If A = [a_{ij}] and B = [b_{ij}] are matrices of the same order n \times m, then their sum is the matrix C = [c_{ij}] of order n \times m wherec_{ij} = a_{ij} + b_{ij}

Problem 1.8

LetA = \begin{bmatrix} 9 & -3 \\ 4 & 1 \\ 2 & 0 \end{bmatrix}, \quad B = \begin{bmatrix} 5 & 2 \\ -1 & 6 \\ 3 & 4 \end{bmatrix}, \quad C = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 2 \\ 1 & 1 \\ 3 & 5 \end{bmatrix}

Find the sums A + B and B + C.

The following theorem gives us a way of checking if the given system of linear equations does have or does not have a solution.

Theorem (Kronecker - Capelli)

System of linear equations AX = B has at least one solution if and only ifr(A) = r(A|B).

Problem 4.1

Check whether or not the following system of linear equations has a solution:\begin{cases}
x+2y+z = 4 \\ 2x+y+2z = 5 \\ 3x+2y+3z = 12
\end{cases}

Problem 4.2

Check whether or not the following system of linear equations has a solution:\begin{cases}
x+2y+3z = 1 \\ -x+3y-21z = 2 \\ 3x+7y+3z = 3
\end{cases}

Now that we know how to check whether or not a given system of linear equations has a solution, we want to know how to explicity compute the solutions (if they exist).

Problem 4.3

Using the Gauss-Jordan algorithm, solve the system\begin{cases}
-2x+y+3z = 1 \\
x+2z = 1 \\
4x-y+5z = 1
\end{cases}

Problem 4.4

Using Gauss-Jordan algorithm, solve the system\begin{cases}
x+3y = 2 \\
2x+3y+3z = 7 \\
2x+z = 6 \\
3x+9y+3z = 12
\end{cases}

Problem 4.5

Using Gauss-Jordan algorithm, solve the following systems: a)\begin{cases}
x+y-z = 0 \\ 2x-y+z = 0
\end{cases}

b)\begin{cases}
x+y-z+w = 0 \\ 2x-y+z-w = 0
\end{cases}

