The main thing about functions is that you can plug numbers into the function, and the function returns back some value. But, numbers arenâ€™t the only thing that can be plugged-into functions.

Example

Let f(x) = 3x-1 and g(x) = x^2 + 5. Then\begin{split}
f(g(x)) &= f(x^2+5) \\ &= 3 \cdot (x^2+5) -1 \\ &= 3x^2 + 14 
\end{split}

Similarly,\begin{split}
g(f(x)) &= g(3x-1) \\ &= (3x-1)^2 + 5 \\ &= 9x^2-6x+6
\end{split}

The operation of pluggin-in one function inside another is called composition of functions. When we are trying to recognize whether or not a given function is a composition of two or more functions, we are always moving from the â€œoutsideâ€ to the â€œinsideâ€, where the â€œoutsideâ€ function is, generally speaking, the one that appears first.

Problem 5.3

Let f(x) = \sqrt[3]{x} and g(x) = 2x^2 -13x + 17. Compute the compositions f(g(x)) and g(f(x)).

Problem 5.4

Consider the following compositions:

\displaystyle F(x) = \sqrt{5x^2-4x}

\displaystyle G(x) = e^{\sqrt[5]{x}}

\displaystyle H(x) = \ln(x^2+1)

For each composition determine which function is the â€œoutsideâ€ function and which one is the â€œinsideâ€ function.
